{{Orphan|date=October 2012}}
'''Charles L. Kuhn''' (1902-1985) was an [[United States|American]] [[academic]], [[art historian]], and Director of [[Harvard University]]'s [[Busch-Reisinger Museum]].<ref name="nyt1985obit">[https://www.nytimes.com/1985/07/23/arts/charles-l-kuhn-83-ex-curator-at-harvard.html?scp=1&sq=charles%20l%20kuhn&st=cse "Charles L. Kuhn, 83; Ex-Curator at Harvard,"] ''New York Times.'' July 23, 1985.</ref>
Kuhn earned a PhD at Harvard in 1929.<ref name="mfaa">Monuments Men Foundation: [http://www.monumentsmenfoundation.org/monumentsmen/ Monuments Men> Kuhn, Lt. Cdr. Charles L.]</ref>
==Career== In 1930, Kuhn joined the Harvard faculty. In addition to teaching, he was named director of the Busch-Reisinger Museum, which was dedicated to the study and artworks of Germanic countries.<ref name="mfaa"/>
His academic career was interrupted by military service in the Second World War. At war's end, he returned to teach at Harvard.<ref name="nyt1985obit"/>
==World War II== Lieutenant Commander Charles Kuhn was activated from the United States Naval Reserve (USNR) during the Second World War. He was a Monuments, Fine Arts, and Archives (MFAA) Officer.<ref name="mfaa"/>
